column5: Shu-Ying Lui (shown in middle), UCLA graduate dance student and award-winning choreographer from Taiwan, with dance students Hung-Fu Lee (below) and Pei-Li Hsu (standing) will perform original works choreographed by Lui
column6: UCLA School of the Arts Los Angeles California 90024-1431 Photo Caption: Upstarts Dance--Shu-Ying Lui (shown in middle), UCLA graduate dance student and award-winning choreographer from Taiwan, with dance students Hung-Fu Lee (below) and Pei-Li Hsu (standing) will perform original works choreographed by Lui at the "Taste a Slice of the City" concerts at 8 p.m. on Nov. 6 and 7 in UCLA's Schoenberg Auditorium. Tickets are $8 for general public, and $6 for students and senior citizens. For ticket information, call UCLA Central Ticket Office at (310) 825-2101. Note: Media are invited to attend a special invitation-only dress rehearsal at 8 p.m. on Thursday, Nov. 5, in Schoenberg Auditorium. Contact: Joyce Huyett at (310) 825-6540.

column5: External view of the Jules Stein Eye Institute
column6: The Institute exterior combines a stylized expression of classic architecture with contemporary functional design. Forty-foot high free-standing marble columns form a colonnade on the building's east and west sides, which are faced with white Roman travertine marble.

column5: Group of men look over plans for the Jules Stein Eye Institute building
column6: Historical - JSEI

column5: Nurse using equipment in operating room in the Jules Stein Eye Institute
column6: Specially equipped operating rooms feature overheard microscopes that magnify minute surgical procedures.

column5: View of mural in the children's section of the outpatient clinic at the Jules Stein Eye Institute
column6: A unique feature in the children's section of the outpatient clinic of the Jules Stein Eye Institute at UCLA is a large ceramic mural designed by artist Mary Blair under the supervision of Walt Disney. Theme of the Mural is "The Small World of Children."

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Two students interact with the Mineral Exhibit at the traveling Atomic Energy Exhibit, 1951
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51 A student visitor to the Traveling Atomic Energy Exhibition presses one of the buttons on the Mineral Exhibit. His friend watches while a map of the world lights up showing the locations of uranium-bearing ores. The Exhibition is now touring the country under the joint sponsorship of the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy (Oak Ridge, Tennessee.).

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Students gathered in front of a model atomic pile at the Atomic Energy Exhibit
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51 While students watch, the model atomic pile shown above makes ordinary dimes radioactive as a demonstration of radioisotope production. Souvenir radioactive dimes are made for large numbers of students and others who visit the Traveling Atomic Energy Exhibition. The Exhibition, now touring nationally, is co-sponsored by the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy.

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Mr. and Mrs. G.F. Keeley of Homewood, Alabama show children, Carol and Steve a participation exhibit at the Atomic Energy Exhibit
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51 Mr. and Mrs. G.F. Keeley of Homewood, Alabama, show children, Carol and Steve, the chief location of uranium ore by flashing lights on a map of the world. Participation exhibits like this one showing the raw materials of atomic energy are among the features of the Traveling Atomic Energy Exhibition, co-sponsored by the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy (Oak Ridge, Tennessee).

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Earl Duff, a Museum staff member, presents for U.S. State Department officials, E. Lee Fairley and Henry J. Kellerman
column6: Earl Duff, of the Museum staff, explains the principles of a nuclear reactor from a model on display with the NUEA atomic energy exhibition to U.S. State Department officials E. Lee Fairley (left) and Henry J. Kellerman.

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: View of the Atomic Energy Exhibit as it was set up in Birmingham, Alabama
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51 Atomic energy went under "the big top" at the State Fair in Birmingham, Ala., during the premiere of the Traveling Atomic Energy Exhibition. Shown above are some of the exhibitions in the tent. The Exhibition has a total of over thirty displays which are traveling as a unit under the auspices of the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy.

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Visitors look on as exhibit presenter demonstrates the Dunning Experiment, October 1951
column6: In the Dunning experiment, which demonstrates the process of fission, is a large fluorescent tube which lights up to mark each fissioning of an atom. At the same time an oscilloscope records a vertical jump in its horizontal beam, and an electric diagram lights up, illustrating an atom which has been split into two parts. The dunning experiment is a part of thirty-odd atomic energy exhibits which are now touring the nation under the auspices of the National University Extension Association, the Atomic Energy Commission and the American Museum of Atomic Energy Commission and the American Museum of Atomic Energy in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Visitors at the Atomic Energy Exhibit examine panels that provide basic facts about the atom, October 1951
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51  Visitors at the Traveling Atomic Energy Exhibition examine panels giving basic facts about the atom. The Exhibition, which covers the main phases of the atomic energy program in some thirty exhibits, is being shown across the country by the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy, co-sponsors of the enterprise.

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: A group stands listening to an exhibit presenter at the Atomic Energy Exhibit, October 1951
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51 Visitors to the Traveling Atomic Energy Exhibition, co-sponsored by the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy, are impressed as they watch a demonstration of the Wilson Cloud Chamber. The Cloud Chamber, atomic research tool, shown tracts of atomic particles which are too small to be seen under even the most powerful microscope.

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: M.T. Clark, Acting Chairman of the University Relations Division, stands in front of introductory panel with visitor to the exhibit
column6: One of the introductory panels in the NUEA atomic energy show is explained to visitor by M.T. Clark, Acting Chairman, University Relations Division, Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies. It is part of a series of panels which orient the visitor in the basic facts of atomic energy so that other exhibits will be better understood.

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Students look on as an exhibit demonstrator explains equipment at the traveling Atomic Energy Exhibit
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51 While grade school students watch, a demonstrator explains equipment which splits atoms of uranium and measures the energy released. The exhibit shown here in part is one of over thirty atomic energy exhibits now traveling across the country under the auspices of the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy (Oak Ridge, Tennessee).

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Officials inspect exhibit which introduces the traveling Atomic Energy Exhibit at its premiere showing in Birmingham, Alabama
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51 Officials inspect exhibits which introduce the Traveling Atomic Energy Exhibition during its premiere showing in Birmingham, Alabama. From Birmingham the Exhibition will continue on a national tour sponsored by the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy (Oak Ridge, Tennessee). Above, left to right, are: George Glasheen, Chief, Educational Services Section, Atomic Energy Commission; John R. Morton, Director of Continuation Education, University of Alabama; and David L. DeJarnette, Chairman, Museum Division, Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies.

column4: Atomic Energy Exhibit- 1951 (Oak Ridge Institute of Nuclear Studies)
column5: Students view the Dunning exhibit at the traveling Atomic Energy Exhibit, 1951
column6: NUEA AMAE Exhibition Oct/51 One of over thirty exhibits in the Traveling Atomic Energy Exhibition is the Dunning Exhibit which students are watching here. This Exhibit explains the release of energy by splitting of uranium atoms, a process which is actually demonstrated. The entire Exhibition is sponsored by the National University Extension Association and the American Museum of Atomic Energy (Oak Ridge, Tennessee).

column6: Handy-sized atomic radiation indicator called a "dosimeter" is here displayed by Frances Miller of the Atomic Energy Projecton the Los Angeles campus. Pilot model in Miss Miller's right hand can be reduced to the pocket-sized three-vial type. U.C.L.A. nuclear physicists are studying various instruments to find most practical type.

column5: Radiation indicators produced by the experiments of the U.ca.L.A. Atomic Energy Project
column6: Experiments at the U.C.L.A. Atomic Energy Project have produced increasingly promising atomic radiation indicators. One is about the size of a book of matches, the other resembles a small fountain pen. Both employ a chloroform-dye indicator principle and are designed for use by civilian defense workers or other personnel in a potentially dangerous radiation area.

column5: Frances Miller of the Atomic Energy Project holds up a "dosimeter," an atomic radiation indicator
column6: Latest pencil-sized atomic radiation indicator called a "dosimeter" is shown in right hand of U.C.L.A. Atomic Energy Project employee Frances Miller. Set to indicate amount of radiation person receives, it can be sheated in metal case, worn handsomely next to pocket pen and pencil set. U.C.L.A. nuclear physisists are studying various instruments to find most practical type.

column5: Dr. Chauncey Starr and Dr. Stafford L. Warren with first atomic energy reactor, ca. 1955
column6: Nuclear medicine and radiation biology   Includes note from North American Aviation, Inc.: For Release After 10 A.M. PDT Tuesday, July 12, 1955.   ATOMIC REACTOR FOR MEDICAL RESEARCH--The first atomic energy reactor specifically designed for medical research will be built for the Medical Center at the University of California at Los Angeles by North American Aviation. Gamma rays and neutrons will be produced by atomic fission in the reactor and can be directed to a patient under treatment for cancer just a few feet away. Dr. Chauncey Starr, left, Vice President in charge of North American's Nuclear Engineering and Manufacturing Division, and Dr. Stafford L. Warren, Dean of the U.C.L.A. Medical School, discuss model of the 50 kilowatt reactor. Scheduled for completion in about one year the reactor will be used for other nuclear studies in addition to medical research. - 30 -     GL71255

column6: Wish you were here --> The Powell Library - UCLA UCLA's original library building, a landmark on the central campus since 1929, is named for Lawrence Clark Powell, former University Librarian and founding Dean of the School of Library Service. The undergraduate College Library occupies the major part of this Romanesque-Byzantine style building.     Dear Steve, Becky, Pretty Debbie, Tom, Amy - coudn't find a postcard of a potato field or a suburban housing development. So I settled for this. N.Y. is great - plenty of hot, humid air + greasy pizza. We're getting a huge dose of love + attention. greasy pizza + attention. what else could you ask for? give my best to Bernie if you ever hear from him again   -Debby   Address   Oral History Program 136 Powell Library UCLA Los Angeles, CA 90024

Haynes; Dr. Vincent, former president of Rockefeller Institute; J. Arthur Thomson, of Aberdeen University, Scotland, distinguished scientist; Dr. Robert G. Sproul, Vice-President and Comptroller, University of California; President W.W. Campbell, University of California; Dean Blyth Webster, St. Andrews University, Scotland; Regent Mortimer Fleishhacker; Regent Edward A. Dickson; and Regent Guy C. Earl.      E.A. Dickson Papers

column5: Lt. William Chapin of the 82nd Fighter-Intercepter Squadron explains basic jet fighter maneuvers to Professor Lee P. Delsasse
column6: Professor Lee P. Delsasse of UCLA is clarified on basic jet fighter maneuvers by Lt. William Chapin of the 82nd Fighter-Intercepter Squadron during a tour of Hamilton AFB, Calif., July 25-27: by the Los Angeles school faculty member. Delsasso and Professor Raymond H. Fisher were among two groups of 35 western college representatives which were guests of the Fourth Air Force ROTC Summer Encampment at Hamilton AFB. The guests represented 17 western colleges, including UCLA and Loyola, which sent over 500 students to the six-week ROTC Encampment. All of the cadets undergoing the summer training are being prepared, both in schoool and at camp, for reserve commissions in the Air Force as administrative and logistics specialists.   (PIO, Summer ROTC Encampment (Hamilton AFB

column6: Rieber Hall   Rieber Hall  UCLA DORM---Architect's rendering depicts UCLA's third new residence hall as it will look upon completion in September, 1963. Bids will be solicited in August and construction will start this fall on the seven-story, $5,000,000 structure. It will house 824 men and women students and will be located on the rolling hills west of the/central campus. Financed from loan sources, it is self-amortizing.   -- Welton Becket photo

column6: Dear Alumnus: In 1969, the first man walked on the moon. In an instant, centuries of dream and speculation became reality, and the world watched itself step into the future. In 1969, UCLA has been celebrating its fiftieth anniversary, pointing with pride to a history of tremendous growth and progress. As we step into the future, however, we begin to wonder...will the second fifty years live up to the promise of the first fifty? With the rising costs of education, such progress will be possible only if UCLA enlists broader private support. State funds have increased steadily over the past decade, but proportionate to the total budget, they have decreased about 25%. Your contribution can provide vital unrestricted funds-money to be used where the need is greatest. Every gift, large or small, helps UCLA to achieve its goal of quality in education. The new concept of the Annual Fund was created with the future in mind; it assists in assuring that UCLA will continue to be among the best, not just adequate.   Now is the time to give, because an end-of-the-year contribution may prove to be a tax advantage to you. May I also remind you that a gift of $100 or more qualifies you as a member of the Chancellor's Honor Roll as well as a donor to Annual Fund I.    On behalf of myself and UCLA, let me extend to you my warmest wishes for the holiday season.  Walter Cunningham, National Chairman  UCLA Annual Fund I (July 1, 1969-June 30, 1970)  P.S. If you have already given to Annual Fund I or the Chancellor's Honor Roll, please accept my additional thanks.

column6: University of California at Mount Hamilton  The celestial heavens are the laboratories for the astronomical studies and research of students at Lick Observatory on Mount Hamilton in Santa Clara county. Supplementing their work, which is carried on under the direction of William H. Wright, students are required to act as assistants to members of the faculty in designated capacities. Through observation and astronomical photography, many valuable contributions have been given to the world of sciences by this division of the University of California and its many stations located at various points throughout the world. Also under the supervision of the University and considered with the Lick Observatory is the observatory on Mount Wilson where students and faculty alike add facts to the knowledge already made history by science. Thus the students of the university study the heavens with finest of equipment and with the best teacher, practical experience, governed by an experienced and noted faculty.

column6: Sproul   UCLA'S SPROUL HALL---Construction will start late in August on a new student residence hall to be named after Robert Gordon Sproul, retired University president, and Mrs. Sproul. column6: Sproul Residence Hall at UCLA Los Angeles, California   Named for Robert Gordon Sproul - for many years as-sociated with the University of California at Berkeley - this seven-story building is the second of eight residence halls to be built at UCLA. It is furnished with expansive lounge, recreational and dining facilities.

column5: Student demonstration protesting suspension of fellow students, November, 1, 1934
column6: 1934 Nov 1  Student Activism   11-1-34  Students of the University of California at Los Angeles are shown as they staged a demonstration in protest over the suspension of four students and a girl graduate student on charges of promoting radical movements. The students suspended (shown at top, left to right) were John Burnside, president of the student body; Thomas Lambert, president of the men's board; Miss Celeste Strack, former university debater; Sidney Zsagri, chairman of the forensic board, and Mendel Lieberman, chairman of the scholarship committee.    [Daily News-Wide World photo.]   [UA 435]  [Univ Archives 99 student demonstrations]

column5: James Whitmore, Cloris Leachman, and Donnelly Rhodes in University Extension Theatre Group "P.S. 193", ca. 1962
column6: Violence in A University Setting -- (From left) James Whitmore, Cloris Leachman, and Donnelly Rhodes unleash explosive emotions in the provocative drama "P.S. 193", as presented in its West Coast premiere by University Extension's Theatre Group at UCLA, beginning Friday (April 3) through May 10 at 8:30 p.m. in the Humanities Building Auditorium. Play deals with events which erupt on campus when a professor's intellectual fortress is challenged by the brute force of one student who sets out to destroy his instructor. Sydney Pollack directs the David Rayfield script, recently selected as one of the ten best plays of the 1962-63 New York season.   University of California University Extension Office of Public Information Los Angeles 24, California 478-9711 or 272-8911, station 2509

column5: Dr. Wilfrid J. Dixon discussing current projects at Health Sciences Computing Facility with Dr. Sherman M. Mellinkoff and Dr. Foster Sherwood
column6: Return by Pickerell similar to p. 128 chp 10  The UCLA Health Sciences Computing Facility, the largest of its kind in the nation was dedicated in 1963.  More than 100 medical research projects at UCLA are currently receiving computer support at the University's new Health Sciences Computing Facility--the nation's largest data processing center for medical research. Dr. Wilfrid J. Dixon, right, is director of the new facility, which consists of powerful IBM 7094 and 1410 data processing systems. Here he discusses current projects with Dr. Sherman M. Mellinkoff, left, dean of the UCLA School of Medicine, and Dr. Foster Sherwood, center, UCLA vice-chancellor. The new $3,300,000 computing center was made possible by a grant from the National Institutes of Health.   # # #

column6: The University Research Library at UCLA   This prize-winning "north campus" building is the administrative center for the UCLA Library system. Its large book collection serves especially faculty and advanced students in the humanities and social sciences. Regularly scheduled exhibits in the lobby attract many public visitors.     This shows Unit 1 only unit II, added in 1970 extends to the left. It is of identical construction   c.1965

column6: Post Card   L.A., July 25. 5 P.M.  Mother Dear,  Just finished my lap(?) work+supper and ready to go home. Trunk left yesterday evening. Let it be known if you get it. Charged nothing for roping. Got your purse but wanted to wrap it well so didn't mail it and can't get down til tomorrow. No job. Have to take exam in Mch. + can only be substitute till then.Nothin' doin'! Write later. Love to all E.     Mrs. Nellie Simpson Y.M.C.A. Eugene, Ore. %7. Eberhart.

column6: D.E. This is where I spend my working hours. The open roof has now been made into a cool garden for the parties & dancing. The low cement bench is my hang out. Picture me there at least once a day. The gold fish pond is our pride and we have 6 ducks. These pictures were all taken in the spring before the flowers were in gorgeous array as they are now. In front of this building the chrysanthemums are 3 feet big. all live in the world yours on 11am (?)   Scanned 2010 Sep 10  300 dpi 600 dpi -> Home Economics Bldg. b c1925 Vermont Ave campus\     1919-1923 I adeenzled (?) here  Kathryn Alden  Miss Esther Jamison  Grinnell, Iowa  Martha Cleveland Grinnell Dorm.

column5: Board of Regents meeting portrait, February 1923
column6: Board of Regents-- meeting of Feburary 13, 1923, held on Vermont Street Campus to consider proposal submitted by Regent Dickson that a Third year be added to the College of Letters and Science. [Seated] - Left to Right - Governor Friend W. Richardson, President-elect W.W. Campbell, Regents Foster, Earl, McEnerny, Sartori, Haynes, Wheeler [Standing - left to right] Retiring President David P. Barrows, Regents Anderson, Britton, Dickson, Ramm, Moffitt, Fleisthacker, Merriam (later governor of California) Mauzy, Jastro, Crocker, and Clinton E. Miller. Regents Cochran & Mills were at extreme left (standing) Comptroller Robert Gordon Sproul and his assistant (Strouble) are seated at right of Governor Richardson.

column6: University of California Los Angeles Campus News Service BR. 22171 AR. 30971 Sta. 280. General plan of the new building program for the Los Angeles campus of the University of California is shown in this architect's drawing looking west across the campus. of the present buildings, the two large structures at top center are the Men's and Women's Gymnasiums. Below them is the main quadrangle, surrounded by the Library, Royce Hall, and teh Chemistry and Physics Buildings. The two open sqyuares below this group are the proposed sunken gardens which would replace the present arroyo.

column5: Exterior side of the William Andrews Clark Library
column6: The Clark Library came to UCLA in 1934 as a bequest of William Andrews Clark, Jr. Its 75,000 rare books dealing with English culture, 1640-1750, are world-famous among scholars. The setting is a landscaped city-block in the elegant old West Adams district of Los Angeles, at 2520 Cimarron Street.

column5: Exterior of the Western Data Processing Center on the day of its dedication ceremony
column6: The $5,000,000 Western Data Processing Center was dedicated today at the University of California at Los Angeles as the world's first university computer center specializing in complicated business management problems. Forty-five western colleges and universities are using the Center, whose heart is the 709, most powerful commercial electronic computer manufactured by IBM. Use of the computer is being given to UCLA without charge by IBM. Participation in the dedication ceremonies were Thomas J. Watson, Jr., president of IBM, and Donald H. McLaughlin, chairman of the University of California Board of Regents. The Center building, whose eastern entrance is shown, will be connected with the University's planned Graduate School of Business Administration.

column5: Side view of the sprial ridge Cyclotron
column6: Heart of the spiral ridge cyclotron is the pinwheel, consisting of four spiral shims (dark parts), which allow continuous acceleration of protons. Light part is the copper lining. The new type atom smasher was constructed largely at UCLA, and designed by UCLA physics professors J.R. Richardson, Byron T. Wright, and Kenneth R. MacKenzie.

column6: Robert G. + Ida W. Sproul Collection (1982)  University Archives, Berkeley Dedication of the University of California at Los Angeles, Friday Afternoon, March 28, 1930. This is a picture comprimising a group of the Regents of the University of California, President W.W. Campbell, Vice-President Robert G. Sproul, and four distinguished visitors. Reading left to right: Regent William H. Crocker; Regent John R. Haynes, Dr. Vincent, former president of Rockefeller Institute; J. Arthur Thomson, of Aberdeen University, Scotland, distinguished scientist; Dr. Robert G. Sproul, Vice-President and Comptroller, University of California; President W.W. Campbell, University of California; Dean Blyth Webster, St. Andrews University, Scotland; Regent Mortimer Fleishhacker; Regent Edward A. Dickson; and Regent Guy C. Earl.

column6: DYKSTRA HALL -- UCLA's first men's residence hall, Dykstra Hall, is now open for business. The 10-story, 800-student structure is situated on top of a hill west of the campus's athletic fields, affording its occupants panoramic views of the mountains, ocean, city and campus. This view shows the south side of the dormitory tower.

column6: Three educators meet this week at Hubert Bancroft School to launch a new University of California Extension class program for the Long Beach and Lakewood districts. They are Harold L. Tallman of the Extension science and mathematics department, who will teach; Carl Ehmann, principal of Hubert Bancroft School, which becomes evening headquarters for University Extension and Dr. Richard N. Baisden, new University Extension head of area projects.    Lakewood + Enter - press 2/4/59  #1  [Lakewood Area Center-Spring 1960]

Dickson Papers HAS NEG UA 18 [Separate note included: Founder's Rock was brought to the Westwood Campus February 19,1926. Mr. James R. Martin, secretary of the Citizen's Committee, after consulting with President Campbell and supervisory Architect Kellum, arranged to have the massive boulder brought to the spot where Regent Edward A. Dickson had stood when he conceived the idea of securing this site as the permanent home of UCLA.]

column5: Group celebrating in front of the Founders Rock as construction begins on the Westwood campus
column6: Return to EDWARD A DICKSON 425 So Windsor Blvd. Los Angeles. Ead WH 7433 [Founder's Day] - "Let the Dirt Fly" - Group in front of "Founders Rock", cheer as first spadeful of earth is turned on new Westwood Campus.  Rear row, left to right- Stephen Cunningham, Robert M Underhill, Robert Sibley,Mr Julius Wangenheim (President of Calif. Alumni Assn) Comptroller Robert Gordon Sproul, Dr Earl J Miller Front Row, (l to r) - Betty Hough (Doughty?) (no identified), Wm Neville, David Folz, Martin Manney Jr., Benton Metzler, Thelma Gibson, Helen Jackson, Natalie Bassett, Vickers Beall, Druzella Goodwin, Fred Houser, Joe Crail.  Note included:  "Let the Dirt Fly" Founders Rock is the heart of the University of California at Los Angeles. Here took place the dedication of the campus on October 25, 1926.  Gathered at Westwood, virtually on the historic spot where Regent E.A. Dickson first conceived the idea of the new campus three years before, Governor Friend W Richardson, Regents, University officials and undergraduates stood bareheaded as the first flag to be raised on the campus caught the breeze and flew proudly overhead.  Those undergraduates are today the "old grads" of today - who will be returning for the annual homecoming.  In the group gathered at Founders Rock on that occasion were (left to right, first row): Betty Hough, (not identified), William Neville, David Folz, Martin Mnney Jr, Benton Metzler, Thelma Gibson, Helen Jackson, Natalie Bassett, Vickers Beall, Druzella Goodwin, Frederick Houser and Joe Crail; Upper row) Stephen W Cunningham (now City Councilman), Robert M Underhill (now Secretary of the Board of Regents), Robert Sibley (Manager Alumni Association), Julius Wangenheim (president Alumni Association) Robert Gordon Sproul (then Comptroller; now president of the University), and Dr Earl J Miller, dean of Men.

column5: View of Health Sciences Computing Facility
column6: ca. 1969 CHS A-level, Biomathematics Dept. Health Sciences Computing Facility; photograph by Leigh Wiener; For Release: Sunday, July 21, 1963 From: Al Hicks UCLA Public Information Office BR 2-8911, Ext. 2342 Shown above is the new $3,300,000 Health Sciences Computing Facility at the University of California, Los Angeles--the largest computing installation for medical research in the nation. Made possible by a grant from the National Institutes of Health, the center consists of powerful IBM 7094 and 1410 data processing systems with two IBM 1301 disk storage files. It is being used to assist in brain,  cancer, heart and other medical research projects as well as research in the use of the computer, itself, as it relates to medicine.

column5: Dr. James V. Maloney, associate professor of surgery, analyzes results from IBM
column6: Health Sciences Computing Facility; Photograph by Leigh Wiener; For Release: Sunday, July 21, 1963 From: Al Hicks UCLA Public Information Office BR 2-8911, Ext. 2342 Dr. James V. Maloney, a associate professor of surgery, UCLA School of Medicine, studies computer-prepared analysis of the constituents of a blood sample. The new IBM 7094/1410 system at UCLA's Health Sciences Computing Facility performs in five minutes the approximately 70,000,000 computations necessary to analyze the changes in concentration of 56 blood elements resulting from one stress condition. The computer simulation program used is one developed by James C. DeHaven and Edward C. DeLand, of the RAND Corporation, Santa Monica, working with Dr. Maloney and Dr. Gilbert B. Bradham, NIH Fellow, UCLA School of Medicine. Dr. Maloney said mathematical models of complex biochemical systems may one day enable the computer to simulate and analyze biochemical structures with more speed, precision and economy than is possible now using conventional laboratory methods.

column5: Dr. Wilfrid J. Dixon, Dr. Sherman M. Mellinkoff, and Dr. Foster Sherwood diiscuss current projects
column6: Photograph by Leigh Wiener; 1844-39-36; For Release: Sunday, July 21, 1963 From: Al Hicks UCLA Public Information Office BR2-8911, Ext. 2342 More than 100 medical research projects at UCLA are currently receiving computer support at the university's new Health Sciences Computing Facility--the nation's largest data processing center for medical research. Dr. Wilfrid J. Dixon, right, is director of the new facility, which consists of powerful IBM 7094 and 1410 data processing systems . Here he discusses current projects with Dr. Sherman M. Mellinkoff, left, dean of the UCLA School of Medicine, and Dr. Foster Sherwood, center, UCLA vice-chancellor. The new $3,300,00 computing center was made possible by a grant from the National Institutes of Health

column5: The UCLA Library's two millionth book is examined by Chancellor Franklin D. Murphy at the 1964 presentation ceremony as Robert Vosper, Regent Edward W. Carter, Mrs. Elmer Belt, Dr. Elmer Belt, Prof. Majl Ewing, W. Thomas Davis, Prof. C.D.O'Malley sit and stand beside him.
column6: The UCLA Library's two millionth book, a 1513 edition of Plato's Omnia Opera by the Aldine press, is examined by Chancellor Franklin D. Murphy at the 1964 presentation ceremony. Seated with the chancellor are University Librarian Robert Vosper, (left), Regent Edward W. Carter, and Mrs. Elmer Belt. Standing are (from left) Dr. Elmer Belt, Prof. Majl Ewing, UCLA Alumni Association President W. Thomas Davis, and Prof. C.D.O'Malley. Mrs. Belt, Chancellor Murphy, Regent Carter, and Mr. Davis were among the donors of the work, along with Regent Norton Simon, Regent Mrs. Edward H. Heller, and Dr. Robert Moss, president of the Friends of the UCLA Library.

column5: Deer running outside the Los Alamos Scientific Lab, New Mexico
column6: 5. These deer, and many others, are regular visitors to the Laboratory. The 70-square-mile technical area adjoins Bandelier National Monument. The building in the background is at the Laboratory's S-Site.

column5: Panorama showing part of the Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory
column6: 2. Panorama showing part of the Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory. The town, at left, is connected by a bridge to the technical area, which spreads over 70 square miles.

column5: Zeus, a giant capacitor bank nearing completion at Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory
column6: 18. This is Zeus, a giant capacitor bank nearing completion at Los Alamos. Zeus will be the power supply for devices used in controlled thermonuclear research. This tremendous energy bank will produce for its first quarter-cycle (15 to 20 millionths of a second) electricity equal to more than the entire power output of the United States.

column5: James L. Tuck, left, head of the Sherwood Project at Los Alamos, John Marshall, back right, John E. Osher, foreground, working on the new entropy-trapping equipment at the Los Alamos Scientific Lab, New Mexico
column6: 14. The entropy-trapping machine, newest of the Los Alamos devices used in controlled thermonuclear reaction research. At left is James L. Tuck, head of the Sherwood Project at Los Alamos. In right background is John Marshall, who developed the plasma accelerating gun which forms part of the entropy trapping machine. In foreground is John E. Osher, one of two physicists in charge of this machine.

column5: Scylla II, a magnetic compression device used in Project Sherwood and possibly the first machine to produce nuclear fusion in a laboratory, Los Alamos Scientific Lab, New Mexico
column6: 3. Scylla II, a magnetic compression device used in Project Sherwood, the program of research in controlled thermonuclear reactions. Extensive analysis of results from Scylla strongly indicate that it may be the first machine ever to produce nuclear fusion in a laboratory.

column5: Scylla G, one of the devices used at Los Alamos in the study of controlled thermonuclear reaction, Los Alamos Scientific Center, New Mexico
column6: 12. Scylla G, one of the devices used at Los Alamos in the study of controlled thermonuclear reactions. Scylla G was exhibited in Geneva in 1958 at the Second International Conference on Peaceful Uses of Atomic Energy.

column5: James A. Phillips, a group leader in the Sherwood Project at Los Alamos, explaining the future usefulness of controlled thermonuclear reactions.
column6: 15. James A. Phillips, a group leader in the Sherwood Project at Los Alamos. He is explaining the future usefulness of controlled thermonuclear reactions.

column5: Raemer E. Schreiber, Leader of the Nuclear Rocket Propulsion Division, R. W. Spence, Alternate Division Leader, and N.E. Bradbury, Director of the Laboratory testing the Kiwi-A, first of a series of reactors to be tested at Nevada
column6: 19. LASL officials at the Nevada Test Site. Left to right: Raemer E. Schreiber, Leader of the Nuclear Rocket Propulsion Division: R. W. Spence, Alternate Division Leader; and N.E. Bradbury, Director of the Laboratory. This picture was taken during testing of Kiwi-A, first of a series of reactors to be tested at Nevada.

column5: A test shape used in acceleration and impact tests is prepared for launching in the Los Alamos air-gun
column6: 13. A test shape is prepared for launching in the Los Alamos air-gun. The gun is used in acceleration and impact tests. It is 100 feet long and produces velocities up to 2000 g.

column5: Looking outward from inside the Maintenance, Assembly, and Disassembly Building at the AEC's Nevada Test Site while scientists are working on a mockup of Kiwi-A, first reactor to be tested in Nevada as a part of the Los Alamos nuclear rocket propulsion program
column6: 7. Looking outward from inside the Maintenance, Assembly, and Disassembly Building at the AEC's Nevada Test Site. The men are working on a mockup of Kiwi-A, first reactor to be tested in Nevada as a part of the Los Alamos nuclear rocket propulsion program. The cradle in left foreground is ready to be receive the actual Kiwi-A reactor, which was operated successfully on July 1, 1959.

column5: Worm's eye view of the cavity reactor assembly being used at Los Alamos in preliminary studies of an advanced reactor concept
column6: 1. Worm's eye view of the cavity reactor assembly being used at Los Alamos in preliminary studies of an advanced reactor concept. Black material at lower right is uranium foil wrapped around  a hollow cylinder. A chain reaction begins when the cylinder is raised by remote control, into the cavity at center of the moderator-reflector tank, which contains heavy water.

column5: Los Alamos scientists set up an experiment involving the use of Hydro, one of the LASL critical assembly machines, as a neutron source for an exponential column
column6: 16. Los Alamos scientists set up an experiment involving the use of Hydro, one of the LASL critical assembly machines, as a neutron source for an exponential column.

column5: A giant sky-hook ballon used to carry a lot a package of nuclear emulsion plates used in cosmic ray studies is prepared for launching at the Los Alamos airport
column6: 17. A giant sky-hook ballon is prepared for laun ching(sic) at the Los Alamos airport. The balloon was used to carry aloft a package of nuclear emulsion plates used in cosmic ray studies.

column5: Clementine, a fast reactor at the Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory, New Mexico
column6: This recently declassified photograph of the "fast" reactor at the Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory shows some details of the machine for the first time. In the closet in the right side of the reactor is the equipment used to circulate mercury through the reactor for cooling. When the machine is operating, metal shield doors cover this machinery. On top of the reactor can be seen some of the equipment used to control the power of the machine. (This equipment has been modified somewhat since this photograph was taken.) The bronze plaque just beneath the stairs shows the name with which the machine was christened shortly after it was first placed in operation in November, 1946. The name is "Clementine." Credit: Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory        June 1951

column5: Wright H. Langham, Assistant Health Division Leader for Bio-Medical Research, inserts chemical dosimeters into one of the plastic men used in biological radiation effect studies in Los Alamos
column6: 10. Wright H. Langham, Assistant Health Division Leader for Bio-Medical Research, inserts chemical dosimeters into one of the plastic men used in biological radiation effect studies in Los Alamos. The plastic men can be filled with materials duplicating human organs.

column5: A child showing signs of impatience while waiting to have his gamma activity checked in the Whole Body Counter at the Alamos Scientific Lab, New Mexico
column6: 9. This child showed signs of impatience while waiting to have his gamma activity checked in the Whole Body Counter. Some radioactivity is normally present in all human tissues. (P.S. : The baby came out happier than he went in).

column5: A young Los Alamos citizen prepares to enter the Whole Body Liquid Scintillation Counter
column6: 8. A young Los Alamos citizen prepares to enter the Whole Body Liquid Scintillation Counter. Normal radioactivity of his tissues will be measured in a matter of seconds.

column5: Wright H. Langham, Assistant Health Division Leader for Bio-Medical Research, and one of the two plastic men used in studies of radiation effects on humans
column6: 6. Wright H. Langham, Assistant Health Division Leader for Bio-Medical Research, and one of the two plastic men used in studies of radiation effects on humans.

column5: Los Alamos mouse investigating a sample meteorite for possible similarity to the chemical composition of the moon
column6: 11. This Los Alamos mouse doesnt like to take anybody else's word for anything. He is investigating a sample meteorite for possible similarity to the chemical composition of the moon. The cheese he is using for a platform has already been investigated. In the background may be seen the moon itself, which happened to be passing by.

column1: Shu-Ying Lui (shown in middle), UCLA graduate dance student and award-winning choreographer from Taiwan, with dance students Hung-Fu Lee (below) and Pei-Li Hsu (standing) will perform original works choreographed by Lui
column3: UCLA School of the Arts Los Angeles California 90024-1431 Photo Caption: Upstarts Dance--Shu-Ying Lui (shown in middle), UCLA graduate dance student and award-winning choreographer from Taiwan, with dance students Hung-Fu Lee (below) and Pei-Li Hsu (standing) will perform original works choreographed by Lui at the "Taste a Slice of the City" concerts at 8 p.m. on Nov. 6 and 7 in UCLA's Schoenberg Auditorium. Tickets are $8 for general public, and $6 for students and senior citizens. For ticket information, call UCLA Central Ticket Office at (310) 825-2101. Note: Media are invited to attend a special invitation-only dress rehearsal at 8 p.m. on Thursday, Nov. 5, in Schoenberg Auditorium. Contact: Joyce Huyett at (310) 825-6540.

column1: External view of the Jules Stein Eye Institute
column3: The Institute exterior combines a stylized expression of classic architecture with contemporary functional design. Forty-foot high free-standing marble columns form a colonnade on the building's east and west sides, which are faced with white Roman travertine marble.

column1: View of mural in the children's section of the outpatient clinic at the Jules Stein Eye Institute
column3: A unique feature in the children's section of the outpatient clinic of the Jules Stein Eye Institute at UCLA is a large ceramic mural designed by artist Mary Blair under the supervision of Walt Disney. Theme of the Mural is "The Small World of Children."
